AN  - 1899013031
AB  - The current research examined the presence of Rosalind Gill's (2007) postfeminist characteristics on the popular reality television series, Love and Hip Hop: Atlanta. The study extended prior research on postfeminist media culture by exploring how women of color adopt, internalize, negotiate, and challenge hegemonic postfeminist conceptions of race, gender, and sexuality. The six main characters of Love and Hip-Hop: Atlanta incorporated actions and discourses associated with Rosalind Gill's (2007) postfeminist themes. The analysis ultimately determined that women of color are not absent from postfeminist media culture, but have been excluded from the discursive space of postfeminism to affirm the White, female, heterosexual subject.
